If you do not have a continuous gas composition analyzer, then annual samples must be taken according to methods set forth in § 98.234(b) to determine the GHG mole fraction in feed natural gas for all emissions sources upstream of the de-methanizer or dew point control, as well as the GHG mole fraction in facility specific residue gas to transmission pipeline systems for all emissions sources downstream of the de-methanizer overhead or dew point control for onshore natural gas processing facilities. Additionally, you must use the GHG mole fraction in feed natural gas liquid for all streams in onshore natural gas processing plants that solely fractionate a liquid stream. For local distribution pipeline natural gas that passes through the facility, you may use either a default 95 percent methane and 1 percent carbon dioxide fraction or site-specific engineering estimates based on best available data. Similarly, for natural gas stored in the LNG import and export industry segment, you may use either a default 95 percent methane and 1 percent carbon dioxide fraction or site-specific engineering estimates based on best available data. In cases where the GHG mole fraction cannot be determined using specific methods, a representative analysis may be selected. It is also essential to develop apportioning factors for fluorinated GHG and N2O consumption for each input gas, process sub-type, process type, stack system, and fab as appropriate, using a fab-specific engineering model documented in your site GHG Monitoring Plan as required under § 98.3(g)(5).{
